88
08:42:00,000 --> 08:48:00,000
Now check if lifecycle policies exist.
For each bucket, try to get the lifecycle configuration.

89
08:48:00,000 --> 08:54:00,000
If the command fails, the bucket has no lifecycle policy.
Print the bucket name and its size.

90
08:54:00,000 --> 09:00:00,000
These are your optimization targets.

91
09:00:00,000 --> 09:06:00,000
Now let's understand the tiering strategy.

92
09:06:00,000 --> 09:12:00,000
Data zero to thirty days old stays in Standard.
Cost two point three cents per gigabyte per month.
Active data. Frequent access.

93
09:12:00,000 --> 09:18:00,000
Data thirty-one to ninety days old moves to Standard-IA.
Cost one point two five cents per gigabyte per month.
Infrequent but fast retrieval.

94
09:18:00,000 --> 09:24:00,000
Data ninety-one to one hundred eighty days old moves
to Glacier Instant Retrieval.
Cost zero point four cents per gigabyte per month.
Rare access, instant retrieval.

95
09:24:00,000 --> 09:30:00,000
Data one hundred eighty-one to three hundred sixty-five days old
moves to Glacier Flexible Retrieval.
Cost zero point three six cents per gigabyte per month.
Archive, minutes to retrieve.

96
09:30:00,000 --> 09:36:00,000
Data older than three hundred sixty-five days moves
to Deep Archive.
Cost zero point zero nine nine cents per gigabyte per month.
Compliance, twelve to forty-eight hours retrieval.

97
09:36:00,000 --> 09:42:00,000
Data older than seven hundred thirty days is deleted.
Gone forever.

98
09:42:00,000 --> 09:48:00,000
There is a trap you need to understand.
The IA minimum charge trap.

99
09:48:00,000 --> 09:54:00,000
S3 Standard-IA has a thirty-day minimum storage charge per object.
If you store a one kilobyte log file for one day and delete it,
you pay for thirty days.

100
09:54:00,000 --> 10:00:00,000
Never use IA for objects smaller than one hundred twenty-eight kilobytes.
Never use IA for objects shorter-lived than thirty days.

101
10:00:00,000 --> 10:06:00,000
The lifecycle policy below filters by object size to avoid this.

102
10:06:00,000 --> 10:12:00,000
Create a lifecycle policy for the financial-rag documents bucket.

103
10:12:00,000 --> 10:18:00,000
Rule one. Transition logs and old data.
Filter on the logs prefix and object size greater than one hundred twenty-eight kilobytes.

104
10:18:00,000 --> 10:24:00,000
Transition to Standard-IA at thirty days.
Transition to Glacier Instant Retrieval at ninety days.
Transition to Deep Archive at three hundred sixty-five days.
Expire at seven hundred thirty days.

105
10:24:00,000 --> 10:30:00,000
Rule two. Transition model checkpoints.
Filter on the checkpoints prefix.
Transition to Standard-IA at seven days.
Transition to Glacier Instant Retrieval at ninety days.
Expire at one hundred eighty days.

106
10:30:00,000 --> 10:36:00,000
Rule three. Transition SEC filings.
Filter on the filings prefix.
Transition to Standard-IA at ninety days.
Transition to Glacier Instant Retrieval at three hundred sixty-five days.

107
10:36:00,000 --> 10:42:00,000
Rule four. Delete incomplete multipart uploads after seven days.
Rule five. Clean old versions of objects.
Transition noncurrent versions to Standard-IA at thirty days.
Transition to Glacier Instant Retrieval at ninety days.
Expire noncurrent versions at three hundred sixty-five days.

108
10:42:00,000 --> 10:48:00,000
Apply the lifecycle policy to the financial-rag documents bucket.
aws s3api put-bucket-lifecycle-configuration.

109
10:48:00,000 --> 10:54:00,000
Verify the policy was applied.
aws s3api get-bucket-lifecycle-configuration.

110
10:54:00,000 --> 11:00:00,000
Now bulk apply lifecycle to all unprotected buckets.

111
11:00:00,000 --> 11:06:00,000
Create a script called bulk-apply-lifecycle.sh.
Loop through every bucket.
Check if a lifecycle policy already exists.

112
11:06:00,000 --> 11:12:00,000
If not, apply a default lifecycle policy.
Transition large objects to Standard-IA at thirty days,
to Glacier Instant Retrieval at ninety days,
to Deep Archive at three hundred sixty-five days.
Expire at seven hundred thirty days.

113
11:12:00,000 --> 11:18:00,000
Abort incomplete multipart uploads after seven days.

114
11:18:00,000 --> 11:24:00,000
For buckets with unpredictable access patterns,
use S3 Intelligent-Tiering instead of manual lifecycle rules.

115
11:24:00,000 --> 11:30:00,000
Riskoracle experiment outputs. Data science ad-hoc analysis.
You don't know when it will be accessed.

116
11:30:00,000 --> 11:36:00,000
Intelligent-Tiering automatically moves data between tiers
based on access patterns.

117
11:36:00,000 --> 11:42:00,000
No rules to write. No guessing.
Enable archive access tiers at ninety days.
Enable deep archive access at one hundred eighty days.

118
11:42:00,000 --> 11:48:00,000
There is a monitoring fee. Two point five cents per thousand objects per month.
For a bucket with five hundred thousand objects, that is one dollar twenty-five cents per month.

119
11:48:00,000 --> 11:54:00,000
If even twenty percent of your objects are infrequently accessed,
Intelligent-Tiering saves money.

120
11:54:00,000 --> 12:00:00,000
For buckets with more than one hundred thousand objects
and unpredictable access, always use Intelligent-Tiering.

121
12:00:00,000 --> 12:06:00,000
Now calculate your savings after applying lifecycle policies.

122
12:06:00,000 --> 12:12:00,000
Write a Python script that iterates through all objects
in your bucket.
For each object, get its age in days.

123
12:12:00,000 --> 12:18:00,000
Calculate current cost assuming all objects are in Standard.
Calculate projected cost based on your lifecycle policy.

124
12:18:00,000 --> 12:24:00,000
Print current cost, projected cost, monthly savings,
and annual savings.

125
12:24:00,000 --> 12:30:00,000
Run the script. You will likely see sixty to eighty percent savings.

126
12:30:00,000 --> 12:36:00,000
