137
13:36:00,000 --> 13:42:00,000
Now let's add stop and start schedules for RDS development databases.

138
13:42:00,000 --> 13:48:00,000
Development and staging databases run twenty-four seven.
Nobody uses them between 8 PM and 8 AM on weekdays,
or anytime on weekends.

139
13:48:00,000 --> 13:54:00,000
That is one hundred twenty-eight hours per week of idle compute.
Fifty-four percent of the time.

140
13:54:00,000 --> 14:00:00,000
A db.t4g.medium RDS instance costs six point five cents per hour On-Demand.
Running twenty-four seven is forty-seven dollars forty-five cents per month.

141
14:00:00,000 --> 14:06:00,000
With stop and start schedule, eight AM to 8 PM weekdays only,
the cost is seventeen dollars forty-two cents per month.
Sixty-three percent savings.

142
14:06:00,000 --> 14:12:00,000

143
14:12:00,000 --> 14:18:00,000
We will use a Lambda function triggered by EventBridge.
Tag RDS instances with Schedule equals dev-hours to opt in.

144
14:18:00,000 --> 14:24:00,000

145
14:24:00,000 --> 14:30:00,000
Create the Lambda handler.

146
14:30:00,000 --> 14:36:00,000
First, get the action from the event. Start or stop.
Log the action, timestamp, and day of week.

147
14:36:00,000 --> 14:42:00,000
Find all instances tagged with Schedule equals dev-hours.
For each instance, check its current status.

148
14:42:00,000 --> 14:48:00,000
If the action is stop and the instance is available, stop it.
If the action is start and the instance is stopped, start it.

149
14:48:00,000 --> 14:54:00,000
Log all actions to CloudWatch for audit trail.

150
14:54:00,000 --> 15:00:00,000

151
15:00:00,000 --> 15:06:00,000
Deploy the Lambda function.
Package the code into a zip file.

152
15:06:00,000 --> 15:12:00,000
Create an IAM role for Lambda.
Attach a policy allowing rds:DescribeDBInstances,
rds:ListTagsForResource, rds:StartDBInstance, rds:StopDBInstance,
and logs:CreateLogGroup, logs:CreateLogStream, logs:PutLogEvents.

153
15:12:00,000 --> 15:18:00,000
Create the Lambda function with Python 3.11 runtime.
Set timeout to sixty seconds. Memory to one hundred twenty-eight megabytes.

154
15:18:00,000 --> 15:24:00,000

155
15:24:00,000 --> 15:30:00,000
Create EventBridge rules.
Stop at 8 PM weekdays. cron zero zero zero question mark question mark MON-FRI question mark.
Start at 8 AM weekdays. cron zero twelve zero question mark question mark MON-FRI question mark.

156
15:30:00,000 --> 15:36:00,000

157
15:36:00,000 --> 15:42:00,000
Grant EventBridge permission to invoke Lambda.
Add targets to each rule with the action payload.

158
15:42:00,000 --> 15:48:00,000

159
15:48:00,000 --> 15:54:00,000
Now tag your dev databases to opt in.

160
15:54:00,000 --> 16:00:00,000
For each dev database identifier, get the database ARN.
Add a tag with key Schedule and value dev-hours.

161
16:00:00,000 --> 16:06:00,000

162
16:06:00,000 --> 16:12:00,000
Test the scheduler manually.
Invoke the Lambda with a stop action payload.
Check the instance states.

163
16:12:00,000 --> 16:18:00,000

164
16:18:00,000 --> 16:24:00,000
There is a trap you need to understand.
The seven-day RDS auto-restart.

165
16:24:00,000 --> 16:30:00,000
AWS automatically restarts stopped RDS instances after seven days.
Regardless of your tags or configuration.

166
16:30:00,000 --> 16:36:00,000
If a developer is on holiday and the instance restarts on day seven
and runs for a week, you have paid for it.

167
16:36:00,000 --> 16:42:00,000
Mitigate by setting up a CloudWatch alarm that detects the auto-restart
and immediately re-stops the instance.

168
16:42:00,000 --> 16:48:00,000
Create a CloudWatch alarm on the DatabaseConnections metric.
If connections exceed zero for five minutes, trigger the Lambda to stop the instance.

169
16:48:00,000 --> 16:54:00,000

170
16:54:00,000 --> 17:00:00,000
Now let's purchase RDS Reserved Instances for production databases.

171
17:00:00,000 --> 17:06:00,000
First, get recommendations from Cost Explorer.
aws ce get-reservation-purchase-recommendation for RDS.

172
17:06:00,000 --> 17:12:00,000
Look at the instance type, region, engine,
estimated savings amount, and estimated savings percentage.

173
17:12:00,000 --> 17:18:00,000

174
17:18:00,000 --> 17:24:00,000
Compare payment options.
No Upfront, Partial Upfront, and All Upfront.
For each, get the offering ID, fixed price, and usage price.

175
17:24:00,000 --> 17:30:00,000

176
17:30:00,000 --> 17:36:00,000
Calculate true break-even.
Write a Python script that accounts for upfront cost,
hourly rate, and opportunity cost.

177
17:36:00,000 --> 17:42:00,000
Run the script for your instance type.
It will show you the total cost for each payment option
and the savings percentage.

178
17:42:00,000 --> 17:48:00,000

179
17:48:00,000 --> 17:54:00,000
Here are the rules for RI purchasing from real experience.

180
17:54:00,000 --> 18:00:00,000
Only buy RIs for resources that have been running for thirty days or more.
Buying an RI for a service you deployed last week is premature.
You do not know if it will stick.

181
18:00:00,000 --> 18:06:00,000
No Upfront is usually the right call for startups.
All Upfront saves slightly more, about five percent, but locks up cash.
For a startup, cash flow beats marginal savings.

182
18:06:00,000 --> 18:12:00,000
Never buy three-year RIs for anything using rapidly changing instance types.
Graviton instances like r6g and m6g are already being superseded
by r7g and m7g.

183
18:12:00,000 --> 18:18:00,000
A three-year r6g RI purchased today may be on a less-optimal instance type
by year two.

184
18:18:00,000 --> 18:24:00,000
RIs are Regional, not Availability Zone specific.
A Regional RI applies to any Availability Zone in the region.
Always buy Regional.

185
18:24:00,000 --> 18:30:00,000

186
18:30:00,000 --> 18:36:00,000
Now purchase a Reserved Instance for ElastiCache.

187
18:36:00,000 --> 18:42:00,000
Get recommendations from Cost Explorer for ElastiCache.
Find available offerings for your cache node type.

188
18:42:00,000 --> 18:48:00,000
Purchase the reserved cache node.

189
18:48:00,000 --> 18:54:00,000

190
18:54:00,000 --> 19:00:00,000
Now let's enforce everything with Terraform.

191
19:00:00,000 --> 19:06:00,000
Everything you have done manually must be Terraform-encoded
or it will drift back.

192
19:06:00,000 --> 19:12:00,000
This is the discipline that separates a FinOps program
from a FinOps project.

193
19:12:00,000 --> 19:18:00,000

194
19:18:00,000 --> 19:24:00,000
Create a Terraform module for managed S3 buckets.
Enable versioning. Enable server-side encryption with KMS.

195
19:24:00,000 --> 19:30:00,000
Add lifecycle rules for transition and expiration.
Add abort incomplete multipart upload rule.

196
19:30:00,000 --> 19:36:00,000
Add noncurrent version transition and expiration.
Block public access.

197
19:36:00,000 --> 19:42:00,000

198
19:42:00,000 --> 19:48:00,000
Create a Terraform module for managed ECR repositories.
Set image tag mutability to immutable.
Enable image scanning on push.

199
19:48:00,000 --> 19:54:00,000
Enable encryption with KMS.
Add a lifecycle policy to delete untagged images,
limit feature branch images, and keep only the last twenty images total.

200
19:54:00,000 --> 20:00:00,000

201
20:00:00,000 --> 20:06:00,000
Create a Terraform module for managed RDS databases.
Set storage type to gp3, never gp2.
Enable storage encryption.

202
20:06:00,000 --> 20:12:00,000
Set backup retention period.
Set performance insights retention period.
Set deletion protection for production databases.

203
20:12:00,000 --> 20:18:00,000
Add a tag for Schedule. Set it to dev-hours for non-production.
Set it to always-on for production.

204
20:18:00,000 --> 20:24:00,000
Use lifecycle prevent destroy for production databases.
This prevents accidental deletion by a careless terraform destroy.

205
20:24:00,000 --> 20:30:00,000

206
20:30:00,000 --> 20:36:00,000
Add OPA policies for storage.

207
20:36:00,000 --> 20:42:00,000
Deny any S3 bucket without a lifecycle configuration.
Deny any ECR repository without a lifecycle policy.

208
20:42:00,000 --> 20:48:00,000
Deny any RDS instance using gp2 storage.
Warn for any non-production RDS instance without a Schedule tag.

209
20:48:00,000 --> 20:54:00,000

210
20:54:00,000 --> 21:00:00,000
Now update your baseline document.

211
21:00:00,000 --> 21:06:00,000
Add S3 lifecycle coverage. How many buckets have lifecycle policies?
Add ECR lifecycle coverage. How many repositories have lifecycle policies?

212
21:06:00,000 --> 21:12:00,000
Add RDS scheduled instances. List each instance with its status and schedule tag.
Add current storage and database spend.

213
21:12:00,000 --> 21:18:00,000

214
21:18:00,000 --> 21:24:00,000
Let me recap what you've built in Series six.

215
21:24:00,000 --> 21:30:00,000
You added S3 lifecycle policies to all buckets.
Sixty to eighty percent savings on old data storage.

216
21:30:00,000 --> 21:36:00,000
You enabled S3 Intelligent-Tiering for unpredictable access patterns.
Auto-optimized access cost.

217
21:36:00,000 --> 21:42:00,000
You added ECR lifecycle policies to all repositories.
Eighty percent savings on ECR storage.

218
21:42:00,000 --> 21:48:00,000
You built an RDS Lambda stop and start scheduler.
Sixty-three percent savings on development database cost.

219
21:48:00,000 --> 21:54:00,000
You added a CloudWatch alarm for auto-restart detection.
Prevents silent auto-restart cost.

220
21:54:00,000 --> 22:00:00,000
You purchased RDS Reserved Instances for production databases.
Forty percent savings on production database cost.

221
22:00:00,000 --> 22:06:00,000
You purchased ElastiCache Reserved Nodes.
Thirty to forty percent savings on cache cost.

222
22:06:00,000 --> 22:12:00,000
You created Terraform modules with lifecycle enforcement.
Zero drift on all controls.

223
22:12:00,000 --> 22:18:00,000
You added OPA Terraform policies for storage.
CI enforcement of lifecycle rules.

224
22:18:00,000 --> 22:24:00,000

225
22:24:00,000 --> 22:30:00,000
Here's what you need before Series seven.

226
22:30:00,000 --> 22:36:00,000
First, S3 lifecycle applied to all buckets.
Check with get-bucket-lifecycle-configuration.

227
22:36:00,000 --> 22:42:00,000
Second, ECR lifecycle applied to all repositories.
Check with get-lifecycle-policy.

228
22:42:00,000 --> 22:48:00,000
Third, at least one dev RDS instance tagged with Schedule equals dev-hours.
Check with list-tags-for-resource.

229
22:48:00,000 --> 22:54:00,000
Fourth, Lambda scheduler deployed and tested.
Manual invocation returned results.

230
22:54:00,000 --> 23:00:00,000
Fifth, your baseline document updated with storage and database spend.

231
23:00:00,000 --> 23:06:00,000

232
23:06:00,000 --> 23:12:00,000
If you have all five, you're ready for Series seven.

233
23:12:00,000 --> 23:18:00,000

234
23:18:00,000 --> 23:24:00,000
Series two through six covered the technical FinOps layer.
Finding, eliminating, and automating cost controls
at the infrastructure level.

235
23:24:00,000 --> 23:30:00,000
The startup's bill went from forty-seven thousand dollars
to nineteen thousand four hundred four dollars.

236
23:30:00,000 --> 23:36:00,000
But there is a problem.

237
23:36:00,000 --> 23:42:00,000
You did all of this. You. Personally.
Running commands in a terminal, applying policies, tagging resources.

238
23:42:00,000 --> 23:48:00,000
The moment a new engineer joins and creates a new S3 bucket,
a new RDS instance, or a new ECR repository.

239
23:48:00,000 --> 23:54:00,000
They will not know about any of these controls.
They will create unoptimized resources. The waste will return.

240
23:54:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000

241
00:00:00,000 --> 00:06:00,000
Series seven starts the second half of this course.
Platform engineering.

242
00:06:00,000 --> 00:12:00,000
You will learn what an Internal Developer Platform is
and why it is the only sustainable solution to long-term FinOps.

243
00:12:00,000 --> 00:18:00,000
The controls you applied manually in Series two through six
become encoded into golden paths that every new engineer uses automatically.

244
00:18:00,000 --> 00:24:00,000
Without knowing they are optimizing costs.

245
00:24:00,000 --> 00:30:00,000
The startup that went from forty-seven thousand dollars
to nineteen thousand four hundred four dollars
stayed at nineteen thousand four hundred four dollars for eighteen months after.

246
00:30:00,000 --> 00:36:00,000
Even as they grew from forty to eighty engineers.
Even as they added thirty new services.

247
00:36:00,000 --> 00:42:00,000
Because they had a platform.
Not because they had a FinOps engineer watching everything.

248
00:42:00,000 --> 00:48:00,000

249
00:48:00,000 --> 00:54:00,000
That is what you are going to build.

250
